"name\":\"How to Measure Windows for Custom Blinds in Chicago: A Step-by-Step Guide\",\"item\":\"https://bensblinds.com/blog/how-to-measure-windows-chicago\"}]}</script><nav aria-label=\"breadcrumb\" style=\"background:var(--surface-2);border-bottom:1px solid var(--border);padding:0.625rem 1.5rem\"><div class=\"container\"><ol style=\"display:flex;align-items:center;gap:0.5rem;list-style:none;margin:0;padding:0;font-size:0.8125rem;color:var(--text-3);font-family:var(--font-body);flex-wrap:wrap\"><li><a style=\"color:var(--text-3);text-decoration:none\" href=\"/\">Home</a></li><li style=\"opacity:0.5\">/</li><li><a style=\"color:var(--text-3);text-decoration:none\" href=\"/blog\">Blog</a></li><li style=\"opacity:0.5\">/</li><li style=\"color:var(--text-2);font-weight:500\">How to Measure Windows for Custom Blinds in Chicago: A Step-by-Step Guide</li></ol></div></nav><div style=\"height:320px;overflow:hidden;background:var(--surface-2)\"><img src=\"/images/products/wood-hero.jpg\" alt=\"Measuring a Chicago vintage window frame for custom wood blinds\" style=\"width:100%;height:320px;object-fit:cover;display:block\" loading=\"eager\" fetchPriority=\"high\" decoding=\"async\"/></div><article style=\"padding:3rem 1.5rem 4rem\"><div class=\"container\" style=\"max-width:760px\"><p style=\"font-size:0.8125rem;color:var(--text-3);font-family:var(--font-body);margin-bottom:0.75rem\">April 9, 2026<!-- -->· Ben&#x27;s Blinds Chicago</p><h1 style=\"font-family:var(--font-display);font-weight:800;font-size:clamp(1.5rem, 3.5vw, 2.25rem);color:var(--text);margin-bottom:1.25rem;line-height:1.2\">How to Measure Windows for Custom Blinds in Chicago: A Step-by-Step Guide</h1><p style=\"font-family:var(--font-body);font-size:1.125rem;color:var(--text-2);line-height:1.7;margin-bottom:2.5rem;border-left:3px solid var(--brand);padding-left:1rem\">Measuring windows for custom blinds in Chicago is trickier than it looks — especially in vintage buildings with out-of-square frames. Here&#x27;s the professional approach, and why measurement errors are costly.</p><div style=\"margin-bottom:1.75rem\"><p style=\"font-family:var(--font-body);color:var(--text-2);line-height:1.75;font-size:1.0625rem\">Custom window treatments are cut to your exact specifications — which means measurement errors are permanent. Unlike paint or flooring that can be touched up, a custom shade cut 1/2 inch too narrow cannot be fixed. It gets replaced at your cost. Professional measurement is free with any Ben&#x27;s Blinds installation, and we strongly recommend it for any Chicago home. But for homeowners who want to understand the process — or who are considering DIY installation — here&#x27;s the professional approach.</p></div><div style=\"margin-bottom:1.75rem\"><h2 style=\"font-family:var(--font-display);font-weight:700;font-size:1.375rem;color:var(--text);margin-bottom:0.75rem;margin-top:0.25rem\">Inside Mount vs. Outside Mount: The First Decision</h2><p style=\"font-family:var(--font-body);color:var(--text-2);line-height:1.75;font-size:1.0625rem\">Before measuring, you must decide whether you&#x27;re doing an inside mount (treatment fits within the window frame) or outside mount (treatment mounts on the wall or trim outside the frame). This decision affects everything about how you measure.</p><ul style=\"margin:0.75rem 0 0;padding:0;list-style:none;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.625rem\"><li style=\"display:flex;align-items:flex-start;gap:0.625rem;font-family:var(--font-body);color:var(--text-2);font-size:1rem;line-height:1.6\"><svg width=\"16\" height=\"16\" viewBox=\"0 0 24 24\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\" stroke-linecap=\"round\" stroke-linejoin=\"round\" style=\"flex-shrink:0;color:var(--brand);margin-top:4px\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><polyline points=\"20 6 9 17 4 12\"></polyline></svg><span>Inside mount: Cleaner look, shade fits within frame. Requires adequate inside-mount depth (typically 2.5&quot;+ for most shades, 3.5&quot;+ for blinds). Must be done precisely — no forgiveness on width.</span></li><li style=\"display:flex;align-items:flex-start;gap:0.625rem;font-family:var(--font-body);color:var(--text-2);font-size:1rem;line-height:1.6\"><svg width=\"16\" height=\"16\" viewBox=\"0 0 24 24\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\" stroke-linecap=\"round\" stroke-linejoin=\"round\" style=\"flex-shrink:0;color:var(--brand);margin-top:4px\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><polyline points=\"20 6 9 17 4 12\"></polyline></svg><span>Outside mount: More forgiving, covers frame edges, works when inside depth is insufficient. Width and height can be specified larger than the opening. Common in Chicago vintage buildings where frame depth is inadequate.</span></li></ul></div><div style=\"margin-bottom:1.75rem\"><h2 style=\"font-family:var(--font-display);font-weight:700;font-size:1.375rem;color:var(--text);margin-bottom:0.75rem;margin-top:0.25rem\">Why Chicago Windows Are Tricky to Measure</h2><p style=\"font-family:var(--font-body);color:var(--text-2);line-height:1.75;font-size:1.0625rem\">Chicago&#x27;s housing stock — dominated by buildings constructed between 1880 and 1970 — creates measurement challenges that newer construction doesn&#x27;t have. Out-of-square frames are extremely common: measure width at top, middle, and bottom and you&#x27;ll often find a 1/4–1/2 inch variation. Varying inside-mount depths are common, particularly in bay windows where the center pane often has more depth than the angled side panes. Original frame materials may be deteriorating in ways that affect whether inside-mount is even advisable.</p></div><div style=\"margin-bottom:1.75rem\"><h2 style=\"font-family:var(--font-display);font-weight:700;font-size:1.375rem;color:var(--text);margin-bottom:0.75rem;margin-top:0.25rem\">Measuring for Inside Mount</h2><p style=\"font-family:var(--font-body);color:var(--text-2);line-height:1.75;font-size:1.0625rem\">For inside-mount window treatments, measure the following:</p><ul style=\"margin:0.75rem 0 0;padding:0;list-style:none;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.625rem\"><li style=\"display:flex;align-items:flex-start;gap:0.625rem;font-family:var(--font-body);color:var(--text-2);font-size:1rem;line-height:1.6\"><svg width=\"16\" height=\"16\" viewBox=\"0 0 24 24\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\" stroke-linecap=\"round\" stroke-linejoin=\"round\" style=\"flex-shrink:0;color:var(--brand);margin-top:4px\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><polyline points=\"20 6 9 17 4 12\"></polyline></svg><span>Width: Measure at three heights — top, middle, and bottom of the frame. Record the narrowest measurement. This is your width specification. Deductions for clearance are made by the manufacturer.</span></li><li style=\"display:flex;align-items:flex-start;gap:0.625rem;font-family:var(--font-body);color:var(--text-2);font-size:1rem;line-height:1.6\"><svg width=\"16\" height=\"16\" viewBox=\"0 0 24 24\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\" stroke-linecap=\"round\" stroke-linejoin=\"round\" style=\"flex-shrink:0;color:var(--brand);margin-top:4px\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><polyline points=\"20 6 9 17 4 12\"></polyline></svg><span>Height: Measure at three widths — left, center, and right. Record the shortest measurement. This is your height specification.</span></li><li style=\"display:flex;align-items:flex-start;gap:0.625rem;font-family:var(--font-body);color:var(--text-2);font-size:1rem;line-height:1.6\"><svg width=\"16\" height=\"16\" viewBox=\"0 0 24 24\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\" stroke-linecap=\"round\" stroke-linejoin=\"round\" style=\"flex-shrink:0;color:var(--brand);margin-top:4px\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><polyline points=\"20 6 9 17 4 12\"></polyline></svg><span>Depth: Measure the inside-mount depth — the distance from the front face of the frame to the window glass or stop. Compare to the minimum depth required by your chosen product (typically listed in the product specs).</span></li><li style=\"display:flex;align-items:flex-start;gap:0.625rem;font-family:var(--font-body);color:var(--text-2);font-size:1rem;line-height:1.6\"><svg width=\"16\" height=\"16\" viewBox=\"0 0 24 24\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\" stroke-linecap=\"round\" stroke-linejoin=\"round\" style=\"flex-shrink:0;color:var(--brand);margin-top:4px\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><polyline points=\"20 6 9 17 4 12\"></polyline></svg><span>Squareness: If width varies more than 1/4&quot; from top to bottom, note this. It may affect whether inside mount is advisable.</span></li></ul></div><div style=\"margin-bottom:1.75rem\"><h2 style=\"font-family:var(--font-display);font-weight:700;font-size:1.375rem;color:var(--text);margin-bottom:0.75rem;margin-top:0.25rem\">Measuring for Outside Mount</h2><p style=\"font-family:var(--font-body);color:var(--text-2);line-height:1.75;font-size:1.0625rem\">For outside-mount treatments, you have more flexibility but need to make deliberate choices:</p><ul style=\"margin:0.75rem 0 0;padding:0;list-style:none;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.625rem\"><li style=\"display:flex;align-items:flex-start;gap:0.625rem;font-family:var(--font-body);color:var(--text-2);font-size:1rem;line-height:1.6\"><svg width=\"16\" height=\"16\" viewBox=\"0 0 24 24\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\" stroke-linecap=\"round\" stroke-linejoin=\"round\" style=\"flex-shrink:0;color:var(--brand);margin-top:4px\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><polyline points=\"20 6 9 17 4 12\"></polyline></svg><span>Width: Decide how far beyond the frame edge you want the treatment to extend on each side (typically 1.5&quot;–3&quot; per side for light control and aesthetics). Add this to the frame width to get your mount width. Specify mount width, not frame width.</span></li><li style=\"display:flex;align-items:flex-start;gap:0.625rem;font-family:var(--font-body);color:var(--text-2);font-size:1rem;line-height:1.6\"><svg width=\"16\" height=\"16\" viewBox=\"0 0 24 24\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\" stroke-linecap=\"round\" stroke-linejoin=\"round\" style=\"flex-shrink:0;color:var(--brand);margin-top:4px\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><polyline points=\"20 6 9 17 4 12\"></polyline></svg><span>Height: Decide where the mount will go (on trim, above trim, or above window) and how far down you want the treatment to extend. Measure from mount point to desired bottom of treatment.</span></li><li style=\"display:flex;align-items:flex-start;gap:0.625rem;font-family:var(--font-body);color:var(--text-2);font-size:1rem;line-height:1.6\"><svg width=\"16\" height=\"16\" viewBox=\"0 0 24 24\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\" stroke-linecap=\"round\" stroke-linejoin=\"round\" style=\"flex-shrink:0;color:var(--brand);margin-top:4px\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><polyline points=\"20 6 9 17 4 12\"></polyline></svg><span>Note: Outside mount width is the width you&#x27;re ordering, not a rough measurement requiring deduction.</span></li></ul></div><div style=\"margin-bottom:1.75rem\"><h2 style=\"font-family:var(--font-display);font-weight:700;font-size:1.375rem;color:var(--text);margin-bottom:0.75rem;margin-top:0.25rem\">Bay Windows: The Chicago Special Case</h2><p style=\"font-family:var(--font-body);color:var(--text-2);line-height:1.75;font-size:1.0625rem\">Chicago greystone bay windows require separate measurement of each pane (typically three) because each pane has different dimensions and mounting constraints. The center pane is usually larger; the side panes are typically angled at 30–45 degrees from the wall. Each pane needs its own width, height, and depth measurement. The side panes often have shallower inside-mount depth than the center. For bay windows, we universally recommend in-person professional measurement rather than homeowner measurement — the combination of angled panes, varying depths, and the need for coordinated aesthetics across all three openings makes this a situation where measurement error is particularly likely.</p></div><div style=\"margin-bottom:1.75rem\"><h2 style=\"font-family:var(--font-display);font-weight:700;font-size:1.375rem;color:var(--text);margin-bottom:0.75rem;margin-top:0.25rem\">The Professional Measurement Difference</h2><p style=\"font-family:var(--font-body);color:var(--text-2);line-height:1.75;font-size:1.0625rem\">Our measurement specialists bring laser measures, level tools, and depth gauges. More importantly, they know what to look for: frame deterioration that indicates outside-mount is better; depth limitations that eliminate certain products; squareness issues that require specific ordering instructions; bay window configurations that need coordinated specifications across multiple openings. For Chicago homeowners with vintage buildings, professional measurement eliminates the most common — and costly — source of installation problems. It&#x27;s free with any installation. We strongly encourage you to use it.</p></div><div style=\"margin-top:3rem;padding:2rem;background:var(--surface-2);border-radius:var(--radius);border-left:4px solid var(--brand)\"><p style=\"font-family:var(--font-display);font-weight:700;font-size:1.0625rem;color:var(--text);margin-bottom:0.5rem\">Ready for a free in-home consultation?</p><p style=\"font-family:var(--font-body);color:var(--text-2);font-size:0.9375rem;line-height:1.6;margin-bottom:1rem\">We come to you, measure every window, and give you a written quote on the spot. Serving all Chicago neighborhoods.</p><div style=\"display:flex;gap:0.75rem;flex-wrap:wrap\"><a class=\"btn btn-primary\" style=\"font-size:0.9375rem\" href=\"/quote\">Book Free Consultation</a><a href=\"tel:+13123610908\" class=\"btn btn-secondary\" style=\"font-size:0.9375rem\">(312) 361-0908</a></div></div></div></article><section style=\"padding:3rem 1.5rem 4rem;background:var(--surface-2);border-top:1px solid var(--border)\"><div class=\"container\"><h2 style=\"font-family:var(--font-display);font-wei